value":null,"year":2022}]},{"id":"buildings-opportunities","name":"Opportunities","sector":"buildings","weight":25,"data":[{"rank":null,"value":null,"year":2022}]},{"id":"buildings-experience","name":"Experience","sector":"buildings","weight":25,"data":[{"rank":null,"value":null,"year":2022}]}],"sectionCopy":[{"key":1,"title":"Low-carbon strategy","subsections":[{"key":1,"title":"Net-zero goal and strategy","text":["Lesotho has not set a net-zero emissions goal."]},{"key":2,"title":"Nationally Determined Contributions (NDC)","text":["The country has yet to update the Nationally Determined Contribution (NDC) it submitted to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) back in 2017. That NDC – which is Lesotho’s plan to help achieve the goals set out in the Paris Agreement – laid out an ambition to lower greenhouse gas emissions by 10% by 2030 versus anticipated levels in a business-as-usual scenario. It said this could increase to a 35% reduction with international financial and technological support."]},{"key":3,"title":"Fossil fuel phase-out policy","text":["There is no fossil fuel phase-out policy in Lesotho."]}]},{"key":2,"title":"Power","subsections":[{"key":1,"title":"Power policy","text":["While Lesotho’s 2015-2025 Energy Policy document provides a strategy for the country’s energy sector, it has not been formally adopted. A draft renewable energy framework policy has also been developed, including mechanisms for procuring both off-grid and on-grid renewable energy, but this has not been adopted either."]},{"key":2,"title":"Power prices and costs","text":["Power prices are extremely high in Lesotho, exacerbated by a reliance on electricity imports from South Africa. Prices increased by 4.8% to 5.6% for all types of consumers in 2021. A larger domestic power fleet with low marginal-cost electricity would help reduce the country’s power prices."]},{"key":3,"title":"Power market","text":["Lesotho imported 30% of its power from neighboring South Africa in 2018. While Lesotho’s domestic fleet is composed entirely of hydropower, South Africa's grid is overwhelmingly reliant on coal.","Expansion of the Lesotho's domestic generation fleet with renewables capacity would reduce electricity import volumes and lower the carbon footprint of its power sector. The country has a strong financial incentive to do so, as imported electricity costs 10 times more than domestically produced power.","Some 90 megawatts of renewables are under development, with power offtake agreements in place. This comprises the 20-megawatt NEO1 solar project financed by the African Development Bank and World Bank, and the 70-megawatt NEO2 solar project financed and developed by China’s Exim bank. When completed, they will more than double the size of the country’s renewables fleet"]},{"key":4,"title":"Doing business and barriers","text":["Lesotho's electrification reached 40% in 2020 and it is aiming to reach 50% by 2022 and 80% by 2030. This would provide a substantial opportunity for investment in the country’s power sector.","Lesotho has limited availability of suitable land for renewable energy development. The terrain is mountainous, and access is usually difficult. Even when land is accessible, it is often already being used for agriculture or residential purposes.","On top of this, the overlap of official energy-sector entities, including the Department of Energy, Lesotho Electricity Co., Lesotho Energy and Water Authority, and Rural Electrification Unit, has resulted in an underdeveloped regulatory framework, a lack of technical standards for equipment, and slow implementation of projects."]}]},{"key":3,"title":"Transport","subsections":[{"key":1,"title":"EV market","text":["The government has yet to implement any substantive policy support in this sector and the electric vehicle market in Lesotho remains at an early stage."]},{"key":2,"title":"EV policy","text":["The government has yet to implement any substantive policy support in this sector."]},{"key":3,"title":"Doing business and barriers","text":["The country transport network is developing."]}]},{"key":4,"title":"Buildings","subsections":[{"key":1,"title":"Buildings market","text":["While the government of Lesotho aims to improve the energy efficiency of households and industry, substantive policy support is lacking. The low-carbon heat market remains at an early stage."]},{"key":2,"title":"Buildings policy","text":["There are no specific laws."]},{"key":3,"title":"Doing business and barriers","text":["Lesotho's building sector is limited."]}]}],"policies":[{"sector":"Power","policy":"Renewable energy auction","answer":"Available"},{"sector":"Power","policy":"Feed-in Tariff","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Power","policy":"Import tax incentives","answer":"Available"},{"sector":"Power","policy":"Net Metering","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Power","policy":"Renewable energy target","answer":"Available"},{"sector":"Power","policy":"VAT incentives","answer":"Available"},{"sector":"Buildings","policy":"Low-carbon heat target/roadmap","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Buildings","policy":"Tax credits","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Buildings","policy":"Boiler scrappage schemes","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Buildings","policy":"Heat pumps purchase grants/loans incentive","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Buildings","policy":"Ban on boilers: new build homes","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Buildings","policy":"Ban on boilers: all homes","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Transport","policy":"Electric vehicle target","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Transport","policy":"Electric vehicle purchase grant or loan incentive","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Transport","policy":"VAT incentives for EV","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Transport","policy":"Import tax incentives for EV","answer":"Not Available"},{"sector":"Transport","policy":"EV charging infrastructure target","answer":"Not Available"